findings:
- IGAIM achieves 65.89% improvement in influence spread over greedy algorithms, 37.59% over metaheuristic algorithms, and 10.94% over top three performing algorithms (p.1);
- IGAIM is 99.56% faster than greedy algorithms, 34.82% faster than metaheuristic algorithms, and 14.70% faster than top three algorithms (p.1);
- Local search improves IGAIM performance by 4-6% across different datasets (p.9);
- Metaheuristic algorithms perform better on networks with lower assortativity coefficients, while greedy algorithms are more efficient on networks with higher assortativity (p.11)

gaps:
- Most existing studies rely only on basic centrality measures like degree, closeness, or PageRank which don't obtain good results (p.1);
- Need for better balance between accuracy and execution time in influence maximization algorithms (p.2);
- Lack of effective approaches for multilayer and signed networks (p.13)

methodologies:
- Novel selection score criterion combining degree, clustering coefficient, PageRank and eigenvector centrality (p.2);
- Network-aware genetic algorithm operators: crossover (NAC), mutation (NAM), local search (NALS) (p.8);
- Local Influence Estimator (LIE) for fast influence spread approximation (p.7);
- Experimental validation on 6 real-world network datasets (p.9)

limitations:
- Current implementation only works on single-layer and unsigned networks (p.13);
- Execution time is slightly longer than some competing algorithms like DPSO and DFSLA (p.12);
- Requires careful parameter tuning of genetic algorithm components (p.10);
- Performance varies based on network assortativity characteristics (p.11)

findings:
- dyn-kpll algorithm outperforms recomputation from scratch by orders of magnitude, being up to tens of thousands times faster (p.11);
- Index sizes updated via dyn-kpll remain compact and comparable to recomputed indices (p.12);
- Query times remain in microseconds even after thousands of updates on graphs with millions of edges (p.12);
- Speed-ups increase with graph size, suggesting good scalability (p.11-12);
- Performance is robust across different experimental settings and update scenarios (p.13)

gaps:
- No existing method to update k-2-Hop Cover indices for time-evolving graphs without full recomputation (p.2);
- Lack of dynamic algorithms for top-k distance queries in large graphs (p.2-3);
- No known method to compute k-2-Hop Cover with guaranteed approximation on index size (p.5)

methodologies:
- Theoretical algorithm design and correctness proofs (p.6-9);
- Experimental evaluation on real and synthetic graphs (p.10);
- Three types of experiments: random insertions, semi-real, and temporal (p.10);
- Performance metrics: computational time, speed-up ratio, index size, query time (p.11);
- Platform-independent metrics measurement (p.12-13)

limitations:
- Focus only on incremental updates (edge/vertex insertions), not deletions (p.3);
- Worst-case time complexity higher than static algorithm (p.9);
- Index size can grow slightly larger than recomputed version due to obsolete entries (p.12);
- Performance decreases as k approaches graph diameter (p.13);
- Need for further evaluation on weighted digraphs (p.13);
- Open problem of handling vertex/edge removals (p.13)

findings:
