findings:
- Central organizations' cobranding increases other less-central organizations' cobranding through direct/indirect collaboration (p.7);
- Cobranding spreads like ripples from central to less-central organizations (p.7);
- Decreasing network distance increases similarity in cobranding between organizations (p.6);
- Combined closeness centrality mediates the relationship between network distance and cobranding similarity (p.6);
- Increasing similarity in cobranding increases total cobranding across organizations (p.6)

gaps:
- Previous studies have not examined whether tourism organizations cobrand as a function of other organizations' cobranding (p.1);
- Limited research on how interorganizational network structures provide information about cobranding practices (p.2);
- Lack of research on social media's effect on cobranding in hospitality/tourism (p.2)

methodologies:
- Dyadic level analysis examining 990 dyadic observations (p.2);
- Questionnaire and interorganizational network data collection (p.2);
- Quadratic Assignment Procedure (QAP) correlation and regression (p.8);
- Double Dekker semi-partialling QAP multiple regression (p.8);
- Network analysis using UCINET software (p.4)

limitations:
- Study relies on structural approach, ignoring idiosyncrasies of relationships (p.7);
- Mediation effect ideally should have used Preacher & Hayes procedure but software limitations prevented this (p.7);
- Low explained variance compared to ordinary least square regressions (p.7);
- Need for longitudinal research design in future studies (p.7);
- Limited understanding of why some organizations choose not to cobrand (p.7)

findings:
