findings:
- Nash equilibria may not exist in coordination games on directed graphs, shown through counterexamples (p.997, p.1001);
- For simple cycles, finite improvement paths exist when at most two nodes have bonuses or at most two edges have weights (p.1002-1003);
- Strong equilibria exist and can be computed efficiently for weighted DAGs (p.998, p.1016-1017);
- For two-color games, Nash and strong equilibria can always be found in polynomial time (p.1012-1014);
- Determining existence of Nash/strong equilibria is NP-complete even for unweighted graphs without bonuses (p.1018-1020)

gaps:
- Lack of understanding of Nash equilibria existence conditions for general directed graphs (p.997);
- Limited knowledge of efficient computation methods for finding equilibria in coordination games (p.996);
- Unknown whether coordination games on graphs with nodes of in-degree ≤2 are c-weakly acyclic (p.1021);
- Complexity of finding mixed Nash equilibria remains an open problem (p.1021)

methodologies:
- Game theoretic modeling using weighted directed graphs (p.1000-1001);
- Construction of improvement paths and schedules (p.1000);
- Algorithmic analysis of computational complexity (p.1014-1020);
- Reduction proofs for NP-completeness results (p.1018-1020)

limitations:
- Results for simple cycles only optimal for restricted cases with bounded bonuses/weights (p.1003);
- Some coordination games have no Nash equilibria (p.1001);
- Strong equilibria may exist but be unreachable through improvement paths (p.1014);
- Complexity results assume weights are natural numbers (p.1014);
- Open problem regarding mixed Nash equilibria complexity (p.1021)

