- The protocol completes in O(diam(D)) time and uses O(|A|2) space across all blockchains (p.7-8);
- Single-leader digraphs can use simpler timeout-based protocols without digital signatures (p.9);
- Leaders must form a feedback vertex set for any uniform swap protocol using hashed timelocks (p.9)

gaps:
- First systematic theoretical analysis of cross-chain atomic swaps (p.3);
- Need for protocols supporting customized acceptable outcomes beyond the basic Deal/NoDeal model (p.9);
- Lack of privacy guarantees similar to Bolt network (p.9);
- Need for dynamic construction and propagation of swap digraph information (p.10)

methodologies:
- Game theoretic modeling of swaps as cooperative games (p.3);
- Graph theoretical analysis using strongly connected digraphs and feedback vertex sets (p.3-4);
- Pebble game analysis for protocol correctness proofs (p.8);
- Smart contract implementation using hashed timelock contracts (p.4-5)

limitations:
- Assumes swap digraph and leader information is common knowledge (p.10);
- Vulnerable to denial-of-service attacks through repeated failed swaps (p.9);
- Cannot handle all types of atomic cross-chain transactions, only swaps (p.10);
- Finding minimal feedback vertex sets is NP-complete (p.9);
- Requires all value transfers to be explicitly represented on blockchains (p.4);
- Space complexity is quadratic in number of arcs (p.9)

