methodologies:
- Reduction from SAT for NP-hardness proofs (p.503-504);
- Game theoretic analysis of Nash equilibria (p.501-502);
- Construction of counter-examples for impossibility results (p.506);
- Dynamic programming for positive algorithmic results (p.506-507);
- Reduction from QBF2 for ΣP2-completeness proof (p.508-509)

limitations:
- Limited to turn-based rather than concurrent games (p.512-513);
- Only considers reachability objectives rather than general ω-regular winning conditions (p.512);
- Assumes full information and non-stochastic strategies (p.512);
- Does not handle weighted tolls or congestion effects (p.513);
- Strategies cannot distinguish between different players' tokens (p.513)

